"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[7703],{87703:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('[{"id":"q1","category":"Theory","question":"The Scaling Layer spec states: \'Design stateless from day one.\' Why is a stateless application server architecture a prerequisite for horizontal scaling?","options":["Stateless servers use less RAM per instance, allowing more instances per host","If request state (sessions, user data, in-flight operations) is stored in a server\'s local memory, a second request from the same user routed to a different server finds no state and fails. Stateless servers externalize all state to Redis, databases, or object storage — any instance can handle any request","Stateless architecture is only required for microservices, not monolithic applications","Stateless servers can skip authentication checks since they don\'t maintain user context"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents: \'All servers stateless (no local memory state)\' and \'Sessions in Redis (shared).\' The fundamental problem: load balancer sends User A\'s first request to Server 1 (which creates a local session), then routes User A\'s second request to Server 2 (which has no session). Solution: store sessions in Redis with `redis.setex(\'session:{id}\', 86400, user)` — now all 100 server instances share the same session store. The spec documents this as enabling horizontal scaling from 2 to 100+ instances without architectural changes.","hint":"If User A\'s session is stored in Server 1\'s RAM, what happens when the load balancer routes their next request to Server 2?"},{"id":"q2","category":"Theory","question":"The Scaling architecture diagram shows the NGINX load balancer using `ip_hash` for WebSocket connections and `least_connections` for REST API requests. Why do these connection types need different routing algorithms?","options":["`ip_hash` is faster for WebSocket\'s high-frequency message passing; `least_connections` is more accurate for slower HTTP request cycles","WebSocket connections are long-lived and stateful — they MUST stay on the same backend server for their entire duration. `ip_hash` ensures consistent routing to the same server. Short REST requests are stateless — `least_connections` dynamically routes to the least-busy server for optimal load distribution","`least_connections` requires session state to track connection counts, so it only works for stateless HTTP","The load balancer automatically detects connection type and switches algorithms — these are just defaults"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents: \'NGINX upstream with ip_hash for sticky sessions\' (WebSocket) and \'Least Connections for API.\' A WebSocket is a persistent bidirectional channel — once established on Server 1, all subsequent messages for that session must go to Server 1 (or the connection breaks). `ip_hash` provides this \'sticky session\' behavior by hashing the client IP to a consistent backend. REST API requests are completely independent — `least_connections` routes each request to whichever server currently has the fewest active connections, distributing load optimally.","hint":"A WebSocket connection maintains an open bidirectional channel for minutes or hours. What happens to that channel if the next message is routed to a different server?"},{"id":"q3","category":"Practical","question":"This code works perfectly with one server instance. Why does it break completely when you add a second server?","code":"// Server-side session store (in-memory)\\nconst sessions = new Map<string, User>();\\n\\napp.post(\'/login\', (req, res) => {\\n  const user = authenticateUser(req.body.email, req.body.password);\\n  if (!user) return res.status(401).json({ error: \'Invalid credentials\' });\\n  \\n  const sessionId = crypto.randomUUID();\\n  sessions.set(sessionId, user);  // Stored in THIS server\'s RAM\\n  \\n  res.cookie(\'session_id\', sessionId, { httpOnly: true });\\n  res.json({ ok: true });\\n});\\n\\napp.get(\'/profile\', (req, res) => {\\n  const user = sessions.get(req.cookies.session_id);  // Only on THIS server\\n  if (!user) return res.status(401).json({ error: \'Not authenticated\' });\\n  res.json(user);\\n});","codeLanguage":"typescript","options":["`crypto.randomUUID()` is not supported in Node.js 16 — use the `uuid` npm package instead","The `Map` data structure has O(n) lookup — at scale, session lookups become too slow","Login creates the session on Server A\'s in-memory Map. The load balancer routes `/profile` to Server B — Server B\'s Map has no entry for that session ID and returns 401. Fix: replace `sessions` Map with Redis: `redis.setex(\'session:\'+sessionId, 86400, JSON.stringify(user))`","The session cookie is missing the `Secure` and `SameSite` attributes"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec documents the stateless session fix: `redis.setex(\'session:{id}\', 86400, JSON.stringify(user))` so all instances share session state. In-memory sessions are \'sticky\' to the server that created them. With 2 servers and round-robin load balancing: login (Server A) → session created in A\'s RAM; profile request (Server B) → A\'s RAM is completely inaccessible, session not found, 401 returned. The spec\'s checklist: \'All servers stateless (no local memory state)\' and \'Sessions in Redis (shared).\'","hint":"Server A and Server B each have their own RAM. Can Server B access the Map stored in Server A\'s process memory?"},{"id":"q4","category":"Practical","question":"During a traffic spike, auto-scaling adds 5 new servers. The spike ends and scale-in removes 4 servers immediately. Users mid-request on those servers get connection resets. What two configurations prevent this?","options":["Increase the minimum server count so scale-in never reduces to fewer than the current count","Configure the load balancer\'s connection draining (30-second grace period) AND implement a SIGTERM graceful shutdown handler that stops accepting new connections but completes all in-flight requests before the process exits — the server drains naturally within the grace window","Use `ip_hash` load balancing so users always route to the same server and aren\'t affected by scale-in removing others","Set Kubernetes `maxUnavailable: 0` in the rolling update spec"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents graceful shutdown: \'SIGTERM handler with 30s drain\' and Kubernetes `maxSurge: 1, maxUnavailable: 0`. Two mechanisms work together: (1) Load balancer connection draining: when a server is marked for removal, the LB stops sending NEW connections to it but keeps existing ones alive for up to 30 seconds. (2) Application SIGTERM handler: `process.on(\'SIGTERM\', () => { server.close(() => process.exit(0)) })` — stops accepting new TCP connections, lets in-flight requests complete, then exits. After 30s, the load balancer force-closes remaining connections.","hint":"Two things need to cooperate: the load balancer needs to stop sending new requests, and the server needs to finish its current requests before exiting. What handles each?"},{"id":"q5","category":"Theory","question":"According to the Scaling Production Checklist, what is the recommended minimum replica count for a production service and what specific failure scenario does this protect against?","options":["1 replica — a single well-resourced server is more cost-effective than distributing load","2 replicas — one active and one hot standby for failover","Minimum 3 replicas, one per Availability Zone — this ensures the service survives complete loss of one AZ without dropping below 50% capacity (2 of 3 replicas remain), while the load balancer automatically routes around the failed AZ","5 replicas minimum — provides headroom for 2 simultaneous AZ failures"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec specifies: \'Min replicas: 3 (one per AZ)\' and \'Auto-scaling configured with min/max.\' With 3 replicas across 3 AZs: when AZ-C fails, 2 replicas remain (AZ-A and AZ-B) — the service continues at 67% capacity, fully functional. With 2 replicas across 2 AZs: when one AZ fails, 1 replica remains — capacity drops to 50%, which may not handle full load. With 3 AZs, the service also survives a \'noisy neighbor\' AZ that degrades (instead of fails completely) while AWS resolves it. The spec also documents: \'Scale out fast (60s), scale in slow (300s).\'","hint":"If you have 2 replicas in 2 AZs and one AZ fails, how many replicas remain? Is that sufficient? What does 3 replicas in 3 AZs give you after one AZ fails?"}]')}}]);